recordings.loc: Seney Township (near  Seney), Schoolcraft County, Michigan
recordings.rmk: Unmodified recording made from path that goes along top of diversion ditch. There was water in the canal.  Vegetation mostly scrubby herbaceous weeds about two feet tall, interspersed with some small shrubs. On the other side of the ditch, back about 100 yards was a mixed forest. Both male and female Eastern Towhees seen, male singing. At one point the female flew and this was the first time I saw her; I mistook her momentarily for the male, but he remained in the same position singing his "Drink your tea" song. At 1:50 he gave a single call. Many Cedar Waxwing songs and calls also on this recording, but at higher pitch than the towhee songs and call. Very hot dry day; temperature above 90 degrees F.

recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. Perched in the top of an isolated 4m locust tree approximately 40m away singing over an open grassland.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

#Editing#
No edits.

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Skidaway Island, Chatham County, GA USA
recordings.rmk:
The subspecies "White-eyed" Eastern Towhee is a common breeder on this island and into Coastal South Carolina.  It is sometimes erroneously listed as breeding only in the Florida peninsula.  This song is one of several vocalizations of this bird which I am attempting to record.  It is was in tall shrubbery, unseen , as is often the case.

I used modest noise reduction and a very small amount of high pass filtering (161 Hz).

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural vocalization. Singing from within dense ground cover, mostly grasses and partridgepea. The most prominent secondary vocalization is the high call of a Savannah Sparrow perched in pokeberry just above the Towhee location. Approximately 10m from the microphone.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

#Editing#
No edits.

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Millbury, Worcester, Massachusetts
recordings.rmk:
Female-High Pitched Alarm call?, Male-Towhee call, male.  Traffic and wind in some of the recording.  Heard male doing it's Towhee call (as it sounds to me) so got a little closer and heard a thin, short, high pitched note coming from the same shrubbery and saw it was the female.  Got the recorder out and while I've been reading both these calls are alarm calls, neither appeared agitated but more making contact calls with one another.  Male also stopped to preen and the female to eat a green caterpillar.  1st time I've ever heard a chip note like that from a Towhee.

Powerline habitat with a mixed wood wild life management area across the street.  Wind gusts kept many of the birds low but they were singing and calling.

recordings.rmk:
We heard the call of an Eastern Towhee, and knowing that eBird wants birders to identify female bird song, we looked and found that it was an adult female Eastern Towhee singing 15 - 20 ft away at eye level in a low tree. It had a brown head, upper breast and back. 
It was near the top of the Trestle Trail near the junction with the red trail.
I used RecForge II with a Nexus 5x Android smartphone.
Contributed for the female bird song project: femalebirdsong.org
